{
  "text": "MicroRNAs (miRs) are short, single-stranded RNA molecules that posttranscriptionally regulate gene expression by cleavage or translational repression of their specific target gene mRNAs. MicroRNA expression is often developmentally and tissue-specifically regulated and is involved in diverse biological processes, including development, cell proliferation, and metabolism [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . It has been shown that inhibition of microRNA maturation by conditional deletion of Dicer1 inhibits embryonic b-cell development and decreases insulin content in adult b-cells [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . In addition, individual microRNAs, including miR-375, miR-29, and miR124a, have specific functions in regulating insulin secretion, metabolism, and differentiation [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] . However, no microRNA has been identified as a negative regulator associated with the low capacity of adult b-cell proliferation.",
